The cleaned-up text reads:

Hello FRC Teams,

The FRCDesign.org team has been working hard recently on a significant project involving their FRC CAD resources. They aim to enhance these resources by refreshing the MKCad Library, identifying several key areas for improvement such as document organization, BOM accuracy, component configurability, integration of models, mate connector persistence, feedback processes, and updated reporting systems.

While the team has thoughtfully addressed common issues, they invite community input on additional desired changes. However, due to current limitations, only specific areas can be modified.

This project focuses on improving the frontend library since the team lacks the resources to tackle backend enhancements at present. Further work is planned in the future.

The transition from MKCad to FRCDesignLib involves releasing a beta version soon, ensuring compatibility with existing tools until the switch occurs post-2025 season.

Alpha testing is ongoing, with opportunities for early access provided. Feedback is welcomed for continuous improvement.

Thank you for your support of FRCDesign.org.

-The FRCDesign.org Team

posts.name: Phil Szymanowski
posts.cooked: I am intending to use FRCDesign.org in the next few weeks for some educational sessions and will provide some feedback on how things go.

posts.name: Phil Szymanowski
posts.cooked:
Had our first session last night and got through stage 0 and began stage 1. Here is a link to the playlist where we will be posting the videos: [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLqRwrJn5RjlVCTkmDnP5gxuOLbVhdlKWy](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLqRwrJn5RjlVCTkmDnP5gxuOLbVhdlKWy). Session 1 should be in there now.

I really liked how FRCDesign.org is organized so far. The order of educational operations makes sense, focusing on navigating and setting up the software, then moving to basic sketch information, and then moving into simple features.

There was a lack of mention of comments and assigning tasks that is included in onshape. This is one of the best things about working as a team in the Onshape environment that should be given a bit more focus in my opinion.

More could be said about when and why to use construction geometry. Similarly with constraints. I often find both of these things are where a lot of people get hung up and don’t understand how they work, or when to add what constraints. This should be included in the onshape training materials, but some more focus on it here certainly wouldn’t hurt.

I didn’t live perform the exercises but rather task the students with doing them in their own time to pickup the skills. I also started off with my layout sketch for the drive train as a derived sketch in the drive train model just because that’s how I like to model things.

Overall, this feels like the best CAD educational resource for FIRST Robotics Competition design I have personally used. Awesome work to the entire team!

posts.name: Andrew Card
posts.cooked:
Hello CD,

We believe the library has enough content to do a closed beta for the 2025 season!

If you (or your students) want access to the new library for the 2025 season please fill out this form with your Onshape account email. Once added, you'll see the app available in the Onshape app store.

While we did not meet our original goal of having every part in the library before kickoff (which turned out to have many parts), we are still happy with where the library stands. We believe it has enough new tools to remain a valuable resource during the season.

Most Complete Tabs:
- Bearings
- Electronics (same as current mkcad)
- Fasteners
- Extrusions
- Gears
- Sprockets

Note: Most of the content in unfinished tabs comes from WCP. We are simplifying the process by handling each vendor separately. The complete library will include every relevant part from every vendor.

Bonus Items!
- Simplified MAXPlanetary complete with Ratio Labels! (Gearbox Tab)
- Configurable Roller! (Wheels Tab)

Note: All images linked in the original text have been omitted as per instructions.
